## Minimalism (do less)
- Default to the smallest change that fully solves the task. Reuse existing code; prefer editing over adding; delete dead code rather than leaving it.
- Don't add abstractions, options, error handling, or tests that weren't asked for and aren't needed. No speculative "while I'm here" work.
- Keep prose terse: answer directly, skip preamble/summary/restating the request. Match response length to the task — a one-line change gets a one-line reply.
- When extra scope seems warranted, mention it in one line instead of building it.

## General Rules
- Before suggesting new implementations, grep the codebase to check if similar functionality already exists. Ask before reimplementing.

## Project Setup 
- Primary languages: Python (main), TypeScript (secondary). Always run existing tests after code modifications. For Python projects, verify the test command works before assuming tests pass.

## Debugging Guidelines 
- When fixing bugs, always scope file reads/parsing to the relevant section (e.g., current log attempt, current run) rather than processing entire files. Verify boundary conditions before implementing.

## Workflow 
- When making iterative fixes (especially for scripts that run against external systems like rclone), validate each change locally with a dry-run or test before suggesting deployment. Expect 2-3 iteration cycles for complex integration fixes.
